{"/service/ndnp/whi/batch_whi_jarlsburg_ver01/data/sn83045293/00542868880/1930072101/0511.xml":{"full_text":"Page Five\nMANY SUSTAIN\nMinor hurts in\nSPORT MISHAPS\nSports, indoor and out, caused a\nlarge number of minor accidents\nyesterday.\nThe only indoor sport casualty\nwas Walter Naraus, 19 years old,\n680 Nineteenth st., who was cut\nabout the forehead when a r oot\nbeer bottle exploded in his face.\nArm Is Fractured.\nRalph Golembriewski, 18 years\nold, 342 Hayes ave., injured his\nright finger while playing ball.\nEdward Growniak, 21 years old,\nbruised his leg in a ball game. A\nfast curve struck Ignace Mayer, 29\nyears old, 248 First ave., and frac\ntured his right forearm. Ray Wro\nblewski, 19 years old, 711 Hanover\nst., dislocated a finger while play\ning ball.\nIn a bicycle race in the City sta\ndium at Fifth and Windlake aves.\n\"William Keller, 22 years old, a drug\nclerk living at 1913 Keefe ave., fell\nfrom his wheel and suffered concus\nsion of the brain.\nFish Hook in Finger.\nRichard Glisch, 23 years old, 598\nFirst ave., scraped his forehead and\nnose when he dove at South Shore\nbeach.\nAnthony Hlarenka, 11 years old,\n1095 Twenty-third st., stuck a fish\nhook into a finger of his left hand\nin Blatz park.\nWhile strolling along the lake\nfront, Gerald Glowing, 19 years old,\n605 North ave.. fell down the bluff\nabove McKinley beach and bruised\nhis knee and neck.\nJohn Compster, 40 years old, 552\nMilwaukee st., was walking through\nthe woods at a picnic when he be\ncame infected, with poison ivy.\nMan ans Two Boys\nDrbwn in Slough\nOKAWVILLE. Ill.\u2014After a res\ncue attempt; failed, William Yande,\n52 years old; his son Edward, 8 years\nold, and Let\u00dfter Feicht. 14 years old,\nall of O\u2019Fallon, 111., drowned in\nMaple slough, near here Sunday.\nBaby, 5, Drowns.\nMARENGO,' Wis.\u2014Straying from\nhis parents, who were visiting at\nthe Peter Miller farm, near here,\nEugene Diyan, 5 years old, fell into\na 20-foot well and drowned. Mr.\nand Mrs. Diyan are from Gilbert,\nMinn.\nCrivitz Youth, 18, Drowns.\nMARINETTE\u2014WaIter Pries, 18\nyears old, of Crivitz, drowned Sun\nday in Wright's pond near the city\nlimits.\nQuestions and Answers\nFrom Washington\nQ. Do water and ice weigh the\nlame?\nA. A cubic f>ot of water at 4\ndegrees centigrade, maximum den\nsity, jweighs 62.428 pounds; a cubic\nfoot |)f ice weighs 56 pounds.\nQ. Where are the service records\nof u&n who served in the army in\nthe World war kept?\nA. In the office of the adjutant\ngeneral, war department, Washing\nton, D. C.\nQ. How tall is the Woolworth\nbuilding?\nV A. It is 792 feet.\nQ. Did the United States su\npreme court pass upon the constitu\ntionality of the 18th amendment?\nA. Its constitutionality was af\nfirmed by the United States supreme\ncourt.\nQ. Where are the Carpathian\nmountains?\nA. In central Europe.\nQ. What does the name Hanni\nbal mean?\nA. It is Phoenicia\", the name of\na famous Carthaginian general and\nmoans \u201cgracious Lord.\u201d\nQ. Were autos that participated\nin the 500-mile Memorial day race\nat Indianapolis Speedway equipped\nwith reverse gears?\nA. Yes.\nQ. Does the United States gov\nernment buy scrap gold?\nA. Scrap gold to the value of\nSIOO or more can be sold to any\nUnited States assay office.\nQ. How can one protect govern\nment bonds against loss by fire or\ntheft? \"Will the government register\nthem?\nA. Government bonds can be\nregistered. The division of loans\nand currency, United States Treas\nury department, Washington, D. C.,\nis the registration office.\nQ. What is Jack Sharkey\u2019s home\naddress?\nA. Chestnut hill. Boston, Mass.\nQ. Wnat is the area of conti\nnental United States?\nA. It contains 3.026,789 square\nmiles.\nQ. Are contractions like can\u2019t,\nwon\u2019t and don\u2019t considered good\nEnglish?\nA. They are considered proper\nfor use in spoken English but are\nnot good literary forms.\nQ. What is the source of the\nquotation \u201cThe love of monev is the\nroot of all evil?\u201d\nA. I Timothy, Chapter 6, verse\n10.\nQ. Who owns Cf.talina island,\nCalifornia\nA. William Wrigley.\nQ. Do waves ever run as high as\n40 feet?\nA. The usual height is 20 to 30\nfeet from trough tiptop, but waves\n43 feet high have been observed,\nand it is probable that on rare oc\ncasions they may be higher.\nYour Questions Answered\nge Ss n answer to any answerable questions of fact or in\nformation by writing to Frederick M. Kerby. Question Editor. The Mil\nwaukee Leaders Washington Bureau. 1322 New York Ave.. Washing-\nU C inc osln 5 2 cents in stamps for reply. Medical and legal\nadvice cannot be given, nor can extended research be made. All other\nquestions will be answered. All letters are confidential. You are cor\ndially Invited to make use of this free service as often as you please.\nThe Labor Movement\nTO END UNEMPLOYMENT PUBLIC\nMUST OWN INDUSTRY-FRIEDRICK\nEditor\u2019s Note: The following is\na verbatim report of a talk on un\nemployment made by Delegate\nJ. F. Friedrick, Machinists\u2019 union\nNo. 66, Milwaukee (and labor ed\nitor of The Leader), to the 38th\nannual convention of the Wiscon\nsin State Federation of Labor, La\nCrosse, during its closing session\nlate Friday. Because the talk\ngoes so sharply to the roots of the\nproblem and presents such a clear\nanalysis of it and of the only\nlasting solution of it, and because\nit was acclaimed as one of the\nhigh spots of the convention, we\nare publishing it in full for the\nbenefit of our readers.\nBY MAUD M\u2019CREERY.\nLeader Staff Member.\n\u201cTlje question of unemployment\nhas been the main theme of this\nconvention. Practically every\nspeaker has touched upon it. I do\nnot profess to be an economist and\nI don\u2019t know very much' about the\nsubject of gold and silver standards,\nwhich we have been told are the\nbasic reasons for the present situa\ntion of industrial depression. Per\nhaps they do have something to do\nwith it. But when we look at our\npresent industrial structure it re\nquires no great knowledge of eco\nnomics to realize that the real rea\nson for our present predicament is\nthe unequal and unfair distribution\nof the wealth produced by labor.\n\u201cThe unequal distribution is the\nreal basis of unemployment and the\nlatter cannot be solved until indus\ntry is reorganized on a basis of pro\nducing according to the needs of\nthe people. The wide difference be\ntween what wage the workers re\nceive and the value set upon the\ngoods they produce makes it im\nposible for the mass of the people\nto consume the products of industry.\nWorkers Real Consumers.\n\u201cThe great mass of the workers\nof this country are the real con\nsumers and the fact is that, regard\nless of what is said about exports,\nthe population of every country must\nconsume the equivalent in value of\nthe goods it produces if a sane and\nsafe economic condition of the work\ners is to be established and main\ntained.\n\u201cAt present the wide spread be\ntween wages paid the workers and\nthe value of products goes into the\npockets of a tew in the form of in\nterest, profits and dividends. As a\nresult of the high interest and div\nident payments, many of our indus\ntries have been overdeveloped.\n\u201cThere are thousands of facto\nries, consisting of great buildings\nand expensive equipment, which\nTest Your\nKnowledge\n1. How did the month of\nJuly get its name?\n2. From what physical\nhahdicap does Thomas A. Edi\nson suffer?\n3. How many times did\nWilliam Jennings Bryan run\nfor president?\n4. Who was chief forester\nunder Roosevelt?\n5. Where is Reykjavik?\n6. What valuable stone is\ncomposed of carbon?\n7. What are the nicknames\nof Moran an 1 Mack?\n8. What was the name of\nthe last czar of Russia?\n9. Where is Governor\u2019s\nisland?\n10. Who sailed up the Hud\nson in the ship Half Moon?\nThe answers to the above questions\nwill be found on the Want Ad Page.\nQ. How many persons attended\nthe Memorial day auto races at In\ndianapolis this year?\nA. About 170,000.\nQ. What is the premium on a\nUnited States 10-cents piece dated\n1835?\nA. It is cataloged at 10 to 35\ncents.\nQ. Can one 1\u201ey tickets for any\nof the European lotteries in the\nUnited States?\nA, Lotteries are illegal in this\ncountry and no tickets in foreign\nlotteries or sweepstakes may be\ntransmitted through the mails.\nQ. When did national spelling\nbees begin and who ays for them?\nWho won the contest in 1929 and\n1930?\nA. The national spelling bee was\nbegun six years ago and they are\nsponsored by newspapers in the\nUnited States. Grade school pupils\ncompete for the prizes. In 1929 the\nfirst prize was won by Virginia\nHogan of Omaha. Nebraska and in\n1930 the prize was won by Helen\nJensen, 13 years old, of Council\nBluffs. lowa.\nQ. How is Red La Rocque\u2019s last\nname pronounced?\nA. \u201cLa-Roke.\u201d.\nQ. How does the area of Ger\nmany compare with that of Texas?\nA. Texas has an area of 265.896\nsquare miles; Germany has a total\narea of 185.889 square miles.\nQ. Who publishes the books by\nRobert L. Ripley?\nA. Simon and Schuster. 37 West\nFifty-seventh st., New York city.\nQ. What is script?\nA. The name was given to frac\ntional currency issued by the gov\nernment.and also by retail dealers\nto facilitate trade. That issued by\nthe government appeared from 1862\nto 1876.\nstand idle for as long as six months\nout of every year. But interest and\ndividends are paid on such idle fac\ntories, and the money to pay them\ncomes out of the pockets of the\nworkers.\nReal Test of Sincerity.\n\u201cWe have been told during this\nconvention of what Gov. Kohler is\ndoing to prevent unemployment in\nhis factory. I say to you that the\nactions of one employer will not\nsolve this problem. I say further\nthat the test of sincerity of the gov\nernor of his acclaimed interest in\nthe workers is not what he is do\ning for 3,000 workers in his own\nfactory. These workers, after all,\nhave worked for Gov. Kohler for\nmany 'years and made millions of\ndollars for him. The real test\nshould come on what he is willing\nto do for the millions of workers\nin the whole state. When Gov.\nKohler commits himself in favor of\nunemployment insurance, as pro\nposed by organized labor, I will be\nwilling to give him credit for doing\nsomething of real value in helping\nto solve the problem of unemploy\nment.\n\u201cThe first steps toward a solution\nof this serious problem are the\nshortening of the workday and\nwork-week, without a reduction in\nthe weekly wage.\nOwnership by People.\n\u201cAfter all, when we talk about\njobs we are not so much interested\nin the job as we are in the results\nof the job\u2014this is, in the livelihood\nwhich it gives us. If we can live\nas well by working only three or\nfour days a week I am sure none of\nus will complain. And there is no\nquestion but that we could live as\nwell on the results of a shorter\nworkday and workweek if industry\nwere conducted on the basis of serv\ning the needs of all the people in\nstead of the greed of a few. That,\nhovewer, cap only be accomplished\nthrough the ownership of industry\nby all the people.\n\u201cOrganized labor is not opposed\nto the introduction of machinery.\nBut we are opposed to having the\nfruits of such labor-saving machin\nery go into the pockets of a few.\n\u201cThe Nash Motors Co., although\nnot earning enough during the last\nsix months to pay regular dividends\non its stock, nevertheless did pay a\nregular dividend of $1.50 per share\nfor the first quarter of the year and\n$1 per share for the second quarter.\n\u201cCharles Nash, president of the\ncompany, ip announcing these divi\ndend payments, stated that his com\npany had followed the practice of\nsetting aside surplus funds when\nbusiness was good in order to pay\ndividends during times of business\ndepression. Where did that surplus\ncome from? Out of the pay en\nvelopes of the workers. That is\none of the reasons for the wide\nspread between wages and the value\nof products produced.\nTakes Care of Stockholders.\n\u201cWhen we know that the Nash com\npany has some 4,700,000 shares of\ncommon stocks on which it paid these\ndividends of $1.50 a share, we find\nthat it took over $7,000,000 to do so.\nThe company takes good care of its\nstockholders during times of depres\nsion. But what does it do for the\nworkers who created the dividends\nand surplus It just throws them\nout on the street when it can no\nIdnger make profit on them and lets\nthem live as best they may until\nthey can again be used to create\nmore dividends and pile up greater\nsurpluses I\n\u201cThe International Harvester Co.\nlast year mad^ a net profit of over\n$36,000,000. It did not pay out all\nof this huge sum in dividends. In\nfact, it paid out only $16,000,000 in\nthat way and placed the other $20,-\n000,000 in its surplus fund, increas\ning that fund from about $30,000,000\nto $50,000,000.\n\u201cThe workers must create value\nto pay interest on this money, and\nthat is another reason for the great\ndifference between wages and the\nvalue of product.\nDividends Up, Wages Down.\n\u201cThese are not isolated cases, as\nis disclosed by the recent reports of\nthe United States department of\ncommerce, which show that, due to\nthe depression, the profit of manu\nfacturing industry during the last\nnine months of 1929 were greatly de\ncreased. Despite this fact, the re\nports show that dividend payments\nfor the first quarter of 1930 were\nsome $360,000,000 greater than those\npaid in the third quarter of 1929\nwhen business was good. Wage pay\nments during the same period were\ndecreased by $310,000,000, the gov\nernment study discloses. 1\n\u201cIf industry can lay aside a sur\nplus, or as we might say, a nest egg.\nto pay its investors during business\ndepression, why can\u2019t it lay aside\nsomething for the workers who pro\nduce this wealth?\n\u201cI believe that the time is oppoi\ntune to push the program of organ\n1 'L\n\ni\nAT YOUR DEALER\nor\nPhone Marquette 7300\n.THE MILWAUKEE LEADER, MONDAY, JULY 21, 1930.\nCIGAR MAKERS\nWIN STRIKE AT\nTAMPANOLA CO.\nA, satisfactory settlement of the\ntrouble between the Tampanola\nCigar Co. and Cigarmakers\u2019 union\nNo. 25 was reached Saturday and\nthe 14 members of the union who\nhave been on strike since June 27\nwill go back to work tomorrow.\nThe trouble arose over the com\npany\u2019s attempt to distribute a non\nunion made 5-cent cigar along with\nits regular union made product\nCompany Yields to Workers.\nThe company has agreed to dis\ncontinue this practice, to re-employ\nall of its former employes and to\noperate a completely unionized\nshop.\nThe union has restored the light\no fthe company to the use of the\nunion label and has again assured\nthe company that it may handle a\n5-cent cigar provided such cigars\nare either bought from a union fac\ntory or manufactured in its own\nshop.\nList Machine Prices.\nThe union has established a bill\nof machine prices in case the com\npany wishes to use machinery in\nthe manufacture of 5-cent cigars.\nThe negotiations with the com\npany, which extended over three\nweeks, were carried on by William\nBrandt, St. Louis, seventh vice\npresident of the Cigarmakers\u2019 In\nternational union, and James P.\nSheehan, Joseph Muehlberger, Har\nold Read and Hershel Nolan, acting\nas a committee for local No. 25.\n4 Dead in Circus\nTrain Derailing\nMONCTON, N. B.\u2014Four men\nwere killed and 17 injured when a\ncircus train was derailed Sunday on\nthe main line of the Canadian Na\ntional railways 14 miles north of\nhere. The derailed train was a spe\ncial carrying the Al G. Barnes cir\ncus from Newcastle to Charlotte\ntown and, with one exception, all\nthe victims were employes of the\ncircus.\n60,000 More Join\nDressmakers 9 Strike\nNEW YORK\u2014The support of\n60,000 cloak and dressmakers was\nvoted Sunday on behalf of the gen\neral strike of 7,000 children\u2019s\ndressmakers, scheduled for early\nnext month and aimed against\nsweatshop conditions.\nized labor of a shorter workday and\nwork-week and of unemployment in\nsurance so as to take care, at least\npartially, of the workers thrown out\nof employment. There are, of\ncourse, some employes, whose main\nobject is the amassing of wealth,\nwhom we shall not be able to con\nvince of the justice of our program.\nSuch employers have the philosophy\nthat wealth is everything and that\nlabor should be bought as is coal\u2014\natf the lowest possible price. These\nmen have built for themselves a re\nligion of greed and a god of gold.\nSuch men w r e shall not be able to\nconvince. We shall have to fight\nthem.\nA Practical Program.\n\u201cBut I believe there are a great\nmany people outside the ranks of\norganized labor and even outside\nthe ranks of the workers generally\nwho can be convinced of the justice\nand fairness of our demands and\nwho will recognize that ours is a\npractical program to minimize, at\nleast, the effects of the present sit\nuation.\n\u201cIt is our duty to go out and ac\nquaint the people with our program.\n\u201cLet us go all the way and talk\nof the real solution of the problem\nof unemployment\u2014the ownership of\nindustry by the public and its reor\nganization upon the basis of serving\nthe needs of all the people.\u201d\nThings to Remember\nabout a\nSavings Account\nI\u2014A Savings Account is always\nworth 100 cents on the dollar.\nIt never goes down in value.\n2\u2014A Savings Account is payable\nin cash. You get as much as you\nput in plus interest earned.\ni\n3\u2014A Savings Account grows as\nrapidly as you want it to. You can\nadd small or large deposits when\never you choose to do so.\n4\u2014A Savings Account earns 3^\ninterest. This is a reasonable re\nturn when you consider its secur\nity, its cash value, and the fact\nthat your money is available at\n100 cents on the dollar.\nSave at the\nMARSHALL ILSLEY BANK\n1847 The Oldest Bank in Milwaukee 7930\nMain Office 415 East Water Street\nSouth Side Branch\u2014374 National Ava,\nOn Monday, ear Saving, Department are open txmtmmmrfy from 9:00 A. M. to 7MV. SL\nFORD, STANDARD\nOIL ABE CALLED\nPRO-COMMUNIST\nBY HARVEY O\u2019CONNOR.\nStaff Correspondent\nThe Federated Press\nNEW YORK\u2014Matthew Woll, act\ning president of the National Civic\nFederation, which is sponsoring a\nfederal political police scheme to\nspy on radical workers, laid before\nthe Fish committee investigating\nCommunism a highly spiced dish of\nanti-Russian testimony that brought\nsmiles to newspapermen and pro\ntests from even Congressman Hamil\nton Fish, Jr., himself.\nInto Woll\u2019s melange of organiza\ntions and persons tainted by Com\nmunism went Henry Ford, The New\nYork Times, the big American movie\nnews reel companies, all the New\nYork newspapers, Federated Press,\nthe Telegraph Agency of the Soviet\nUnion, various New York movie\nhouses, Owen D. Young, General\nElectric, Brookwood Labor college\nand Standard Oil.\nWon\u2019t Reveal Names.\nThe basis of most of Woll\u2019s testi\nmony was letters from persons un\nknown to him. In many cases, he\nrefused even to reveal the names\nof the letter writers, because they\nwere Russians whose relatives in\nRussia \u201cmight starve to death\u201d if\nthmr identity were known. This\nbrought protests from Congressman\nNelson of Maine. \u201cYou know, Mr.\nWoll,\u201d he said, \u201cthat this commit\ntee is looking only for facts.\n\u201cAll of us get that kind of letters.\u201d\nWhen Chairman Fish announced\nthat the letters probably would not\nbe admitted to the record, alarmed\nnewspapermen quit taking notes on\nthe ground that the material would\nbe libelous.\nWoll announced that his infor\nmation came from a Russian emigre\norganization in New York. Through\nout the letters similar expressions\nsuch as \u201cterrible propaganda\u201d re\ncurred time and again with pre\nposterous charges that brought\nsmiles to members of the investigat\ning committee as well as to news\npapermen.\nOne of the letters charged that\nthe Bolsheviks have two or three\npeople planted on every New York\nnewspaper, while another protested\nLabor Meetings\nTODAY.\nBrewery Workers No. 9, room\n307 Brisbane hall, 528 Juneau ave\u201e\n8 p. m.\nCarpenters No. 2073 (Shipwrights,\nJoiners and Caulkers), 651%\nGreenfield ave., 8 p. m.\nGarment Workers No. 71, room\n305 Brisbane hall, 528 Juneau ave.,\n8 p. m.\nSailors\u2019 Union of the Great\nLakes, 162 Reed st., 8 p. m.\nSign Writers\u2019 Union No. 770, Mil\nler\u2019s hall, Eighth and State sts.,\n8 p. m.\nTOMORROW.\nBuilding Service Employes\u2019 Union\nNo. 17, Lipp\u2019s hall, Third st. and\nHighland ave., 8 p. m.\nCarpenters\u2019 District council, room\n305, Brisbane hall, 528 Juneau ave.,\n8 p. m.\nCigarmakers\u2019 No. 25, Brisbane\nhall, 528 Juneau ave., 8 p. m.\nMarine Firemen, Oilers, Water\nTenders and Coal Passers\u2019 Union of\nthe Great Lakes, Seamen\u2019s hall, 162\nReed st., 8 p. m.\nMetal Polishers No. 10, Lipp\u2019s\nhall, Third st. and Highland ave.,\n8 p. m.\nModelers, Casters and Model\nMakers\u2019 Union N0.\u2019286, Lipp\u2019s hall,\nThird st. and Highland ave., 8 p. m.\nPainters, Railway and Car Equip\nment No. 392, 808 Walnut st., 7:30\np. m.\nRoofers\u2019 Union No. 65, South Side\nTurner hall, 471 National are., 8\np. m.\nSteam Fitters and Helpers No.\n601, Germania hall, 601 Third st.,\n8 p. m.\nSuspender Workers, Brisbane\nhall, 6 p. m.\nCanadian A. F. of L.*\nMeet Opens Sept. 8\nBy Federated Press.\nREGINA, Sask.\u2014The 46th annual\nconvention of the Trades and Labor\ncongress' of Canada, the dominion\nsection of the American Federation\nof Labor, opens in Regina Sept. 8.\nl|he unemployment situation will\nloom largest on the convention pro\ngram.\nthat The New York Times, through\nits Walter Duranty dispatches from\nMoscow, is pro-Bolshevik.\nSlams Federated Press.\nFederated Press came into the pic\nture when Woll asserted that the\ncongressional directory shows Lau\nrence Todd, the Washington Fed\nerated Press correspondent, to be\nWashington correspondent for the\ntelegraph agency of the soviet\nunion, whose headquarters are lo\ncated in Associated Press offices in\nNew York.\nFederated Press, which Woll said\n\u201cpretended to report ajl the news\nof all the factions of the' labor move\nment and is especially favorable to\nthe Communists\u201d received $5,000\nlast year from the American Fund\nfor Public Service, which also con\ntributes to Brookwood Labor col\nlege, the National Association for\nthe Advancement of the Colored\nPeople and other organizations, he\ndeclared.\nWoll himself disavowed all re\nsponsibility for his letters.\n\u201cWhether they are true or not I\nleave to the committee to find out,\u201d\nhe said.\nEvidence 8 Years Old.\nWith these documents he submit\nted \u201c1,000 pages of testimony which\nhe said Samuel Gompers, late Amer\nican Federation 4 of Labor president,\nhad offered to submit to a senate\ncommittee in 1922. The senate com\nmittee, for some reason he didn\u2019t\nknow, refused to hear the testimony\nand adjourned. He offered it to the\nFish committee.\nPressed for information on the\nAmerican Fund for Public Service,\nWoll responded that \u201cFoster used\nto be a board member.\u201d Asked if he\nwere now, Woll did not know. Asked\nif there were any Communists on\nthe fund\u2019s board now, Woll was\nequally hazy.\nMore serious was the morning's\ntestimony. Inspector John D. Lyons\nof the bomb squad told what pur\nported to be a police history of Com\nmunist strikes in New York since\n1926, in which he claimed violence\nhad been a major factor.\nInspector Lyons opposes charging\nradicals with felonious assault be\ncause \u201cjuries aren\u2019t educated yet\u201d\nand acquit them. He advocated\ncharging them with simple assault\nso they can be tried without jury\nin special sessions court by thr^e\njudges, as were William Z. Foster\nand four others in the unemploy\nment demonstration of March 6.\nJustice Mitchell May blandly ad\nmitted that he was not sure whether\nhe made an \u201cunbiased decision\u201d in\na shoe worker\u2019s trial for the\n\u201cthought of Communism in America\nis so terrible to every lawyer.\u201d A\ncity detective revealed that police\ninformation on Communist activi\nties \u2014for all the undercover men \u2014is\nabout two years old.\nX\nj Ww\n/W4r L i! *l* i\ny\\\nTHE MUSE\u2019S\nN I G UTMARE\nIN Music\u2019s darkest hour, amidst the din of Canned Music in Theatres, there\nis still a ray of Lope \u2014THE MUSIC DEFENSE LEAGUE.\nGrown in a few months to the proportions of a major public movement, the\nMusic Defense League is carrying on the greatest cultural struggle of modern times.\nMillions are joining it in protest against corruption of an art by soulless mecha\nnization*\nW mucic in cahh^J AMERICAN FEDERATION OF MUSICIANS\nIt you prefer living music to canned i 440 Broadway New York, n.y.\nGentlemen: Without further obligation on my part,\nmusic in the theatre, add your voice please enroU my name in the Music Defense League\nas one who is opposed to the elimination of Living\nMusic from the Theatre.\nto these millions by SIGNING AND Ncme\nI\nAddress _.....~..\u2122.\nMAILING THE COUPON.\nTHE AM ERI CAN\nFEDERATION OF MUSICIANS\n^Comprising 140,000 professional musicians in the United States and Canady\nJQSEFH N. WEBER, President, 1440 Broadway, New York. Mt.\nLutheran Church\nNotes\nMilwaukee ministers and laymen\nwill be among those representing\nthe southeast Wisconsin district of\nthe Wisconsin Lutheran synod and\nthe south Wisconsin district of the\nMissouri Lutheran synod at the bi\nennial convention of the Evangelical\nLutheran Synodical Conference of\nNorth America Aug. 6 to 11 at\nQuincy, 111. Comprised of four\nEvangelical Lutheran synods, the\nWisconsin, Missouri, Slovak and\nNorwegian, the group is the largest\nLutheran body in the country.\nThe Rev. Paul Pieper, pastor of\nSt. Peter\u2019s Lutheran church; the\nRev. John Ruege, pastor of Jordan\nLutheran church. West Allis; Hen\nry Vetter, 978 Holton st., and Au\ngust Rosenthal, 31 Washington cir\ncle, will represent the Wisconsin\nsynod. Delegates of the Missouri\nsynod are the Rev. Henry Grueber,\npastor of Trinity church; the Rev.\nWilliam Naumann, Bethesda home,\nWatertown; C. H. Trettin, Reeds\nburg, and J. A. Koss, Sheboygan.\nThe Rev. Herman Gieschen, Wau\nwatosa, acting conference of the\nconference, also will attend the\nmeeting.\nThe main subject for discussion\nwill be the Lutheran Negro missions\nin the southern states. Prof. P. E.\nKretzman 'of Concordia Theolog\nical seminary at St. Louis, Mo., will\nread a paper on True Union versus\nUnionism and Separatism.\nThe annual church and Sunday\nLow Rate\nEXCURSION\nJULY 25-26-27\nRound Trip\nMinneapolis $7.00 Green Bay $2.80\nSt. Paul $7.00 Madison $2.05\nWinona St. 65 La Crosse $4.00\nCharles City $5.60 Mason City $0.15\nSample Fares\nBeaver Dam, Wia. $1.65\nBeloit, Wis. 2.15\nBerlin, Wis. 2.45\nCamp Douglas, Wis. 3.60\nCrystal Falls, Mich. 4.70\nDePere, Wis. 2.70\nHazelhurst, Wis. 5.10\nIron Mountain, Mich. 4.10\nIron River, Mich. 4.90\nJanesville, Wis. 1.80\nKilbourn, Wis. 2.75\nLake City, Minn. 5.55\nMerrill, Wis. 4.15\nMinocqua, Wis. 5.20\nOshkosh, Wis. 2.10\nPrairie du Chien, Wis. 4.00\nRed Wing, Minn. 5.90\nRichland Center, Wia. 3.55\nRipon, Wis. 2.10\nSparta,Wis. 4.00\nSpencer, lowa 8.15\nTomah, Wia. 3.90\nTomahawk, Wia. 4.60\nWausau,Wis. 4.00\nWisconsin Rapids, Wia. 4.00\nMilwaukee road\nLightning Kills 4\nClimbers in Alps\nVIENNA Four Alpine climbers\nwere killed by lightning while they\nwere attempting to roach the top of\na glacier Sunday.\nschool 'picnic of Zabaoth Lutheran\nchurch, Sixth and Melvina sts., the\nRev. Arthur B. Tacke, pastor, will\nbe held Sunday, July 27, at Esta\nbrook park, oh the east side of the\nPort Washington road, on the Mil\nwaukee river. There will be an Eng\nlish service at the church at 9 a. m.\nAfter the service the Sunday school\nchildren will march to the park.\nAccording to the Rev. William\nSauer. Grace church, secretary, the\ncommittee of five of the joint Wis\nconsin Lutheran synod with the old\nana new seminary board will meet\nin open session in matters of the\nTheological seminary at Thiensville,\nTuesday, 10 a. m.. at St. John\u2019s Lu\ntheran school. Eighth and Vliet sts.\nThe Milwaukee Lutheran Relief\nsociety will hold its annual picnic\nAug. 6 in Washington park.\nThe Rev. Louis Karrer and his\nfamily of St. Andrew\u2019s Lutheran\nchurch, Seventh and Oklahoma\naves., will be on their vacation from\nJuly 28 to Aug. 11. There will be\nno services on Aug. 3 and 10.\nArthur Mittelstaedt, a 1930 gradu\nate of the Theological seminary at\nThiensville, has accepted the call as\nassistant pastor of St. Luke\u2019s Lu\ntheran church, Dover st. and Kin\nnickinnic ave. His installation will\nrake place Aug. 24, the Rev. Philip\nxoehler. pastor, officiating.\nAnd to many other stations on\nthe Milwaukee Road In lowa*\nMinnesota, Michigan and Wls>\ncousin.\nGOING\nJ Tickets will be honored in coaches on\nall trains from 3:50 p. tn. July 25 to\nJ 4:00 a. m. July 27, inclusive.\nJ RETURNING\nTickets good for return on all trains\nscheduled to reach Milwaukee not later\nthan 1:10 p. m. July 28.\nTickets good in coaches only\nChildren half fare-No stop-overs\n\nFor further information apply\nJ Milwaukee Ticket Office\n405 E. Water Street, Phone Broadway 572$\nJ. C. Prien, General Agent au\n.jPage Five","height":"28554","width":"21246"}}
